howtoplay.utilitycraft.getting_started.h8=Sieving for Resources
howtoplay.utilitycraft.getting_started.p1=UtilityCraft transforms early survival into a smoother, more rewarding experience.
howtoplay.utilitycraft.getting_started.p2=Learn the first UtilityCraft steps: tools, pebbles, sieving, and early resources.
howtoplay.utilitycraft.getting_started.p3=Craft your first §eWooden Hammer§r or §eStone Hammer§r. Then §6sneak§r and interact with blocks to find loose materials. §aDirt§r and §aGrass§r provide the basic Pebbles and Sand Handfuls, §aMud§r provides Mud Balls, and §aRed Sand§r or §aTerracotta§r provides Red Sand Handfuls. Combine §e4 matching fragments§r to rebuild their full block.
howtoplay.utilitycraft.getting_started.p4=At the beginning, you will not be able to mine stone directly. Instead, you need to craft a Wooden Hammer, or a Stone Hammer if you already advanced a bit, and use it in a clever way.
howtoplay.utilitycraft.getting_started.p5=To get your first resources, sneak and interact on Dirt or Grass Blocks while holding your hammer.
howtoplay.utilitycraft.getting_started.p6=These interactions can drop Dirt Pebbles, Gravel Pebbles, Stone Pebbles, Andesite Pebbles, Granite Pebbles, Diorite Pebbles, and sometimes Bone Meal.
howtoplay.utilitycraft.getting_started.p7=Once you collect enough Pebbles, combine 4 of the same type in a crafting grid to make Cobblestone, your first renewable building block.
howtoplay.utilitycraft.getting_started.p8=Before you can start gathering Pebbles, you first need to craft the Wooden Hammer using planks, logs, and sticks from your first tree.
howtoplay.utilitycraft.getting_started.p9=Save at least one log from your first tree, because you need it to craft the hammer and begin your first steps in UtilityCraft.
howtoplay.utilitycraft.getting_started.p10=With Cobblestone and Wood secured, it is time to craft your first important tools.
howtoplay.utilitycraft.getting_started.p11=Use a §eFlint Knife§r to break §aLeaves§r and collect §bFiber§r. Craft Fiber into §fString§r so you can make your first Mesh for the Sieve.
howtoplay.utilitycraft.getting_started.p12=If you do not have Flint yet, remember that combining 3 Gravel gives you Flint, which makes the Flint Knife accessible very early.
howtoplay.utilitycraft.getting_started.p13=Without String, you cannot make your first Mesh, and your Sieve will remain useless.
howtoplay.utilitycraft.getting_started.p14=Once you have §fString§r, craft a §eSieve§r. It filters §fGravel§r, §aDirt§r, and §6Sand§r into useful drops like §dore pieces, seeds, and rare resources§r.
howtoplay.utilitycraft.getting_started.p15=The §eSieve§r needs a §bMesh§r to work. Start with the §fString Mesh§r, then upgrade later for better drop chances.
howtoplay.utilitycraft.getting_started.p16=Your §eSieve§r will not work on its own; it needs a §bMesh§r.
howtoplay.utilitycraft.getting_started.p17=The first mesh is the §fString Mesh§r, crafted with §6sticks§r and §fstring§r.
howtoplay.utilitycraft.getting_started.p18=Place the §fString Mesh§r into the §eSieve§r, then filter §fGravel§r, §aDirt§r, and §6Sand§r to extract §dore pieces, seeds, and other drops§r.
howtoplay.utilitycraft.getting_started.p19=The §eHammer§r is key here: it lets you break basic blocks into the next useful material.
howtoplay.utilitycraft.getting_started.p20=Use it to reduce blocks step by step:\n- §fCobblestone§r -> §fGravel§r\n- §fGravel§r -> §aDirt§r\n- §aDirt§r -> §6Sand§r
howtoplay.utilitycraft.getting_started.p21=Combine §eHammering§r with §bSieving§r to turn simple blocks into a renewable resource loop.
howtoplay.utilitycraft.getting_started.p22=Now that your §eSieve§r has a §fString Mesh§r, place §fGravel§r inside to start producing resources.
howtoplay.utilitycraft.getting_started.p23=§fGravel§r can yield resource chunks, up to §94 Lapis Lazuli§r, and Diamond or Emerald Shards. Combine §e4 Chunks§r into the matching ore, or §e4 Shards§r into a complete gem. §6Sand§r yields up to §c4 Redstone§r directly.
howtoplay.utilitycraft.getting_started.p24=At this point, you have the core loop: §eHammer§r -> §eSieve§r -> §bResources§r.
howtoplay.utilitycraft.getting_started.p25=At this stage of your journey, you should already have the basics in place:\n- A Wooden or Stone Hammer for breaking blocks down\n- A Flint Knife to turn leaves into string\n- A Sieve equipped with your first String Mesh
howtoplay.utilitycraft.getting_started.p26=With these tools, you now have steady access to String, Gravel, Dirt, and Sand, and you have learned how to sieve them for your first ores, seeds, and useful drops.
howtoplay.utilitycraft.getting_started.p27=This is the foundation of UtilityCraft progression, turning simple blocks into a growing supply of resources and setting up your next expansion.
howtoplay.utilitycraft.expanding_resources.h1=Scaling Up Sieving
howtoplay.utilitycraft.expanding_resources.h3=Upgrading Meshes
howtoplay.utilitycraft.expanding_resources.h4=Compressed Resources
howtoplay.utilitycraft.expanding_resources.p1=After mastering your first §eSieve§r and §eHammer§r, scale up to expand your §bresource generation§r.
howtoplay.utilitycraft.expanding_resources.p2=This section focuses on §aefficiency§r, faster §eSieving§r, better §bMeshes§r, and preparation for automation.
howtoplay.utilitycraft.expanding_resources.p3=For more materials, place multiple §eSieves§r next to each other, growing from one §eSieve§r into a §b3x3§r and then a §b5x5§r setup.
howtoplay.utilitycraft.expanding_resources.p4=Up to §e25 Sieves§r can work together, letting you process stacks of §fGravel§r, §aDirt§r, or §6Sand§r much faster.
howtoplay.utilitycraft.expanding_resources.p5=The next mesh tier is §fFlint§r. Collect extra §fGravel§r early, because it helps unlock better drop chances.
howtoplay.utilitycraft.expanding_resources.p10=Once your §bresource flow§r is steady, upgrade your §bMeshes§r.
howtoplay.utilitycraft.expanding_resources.p11=Higher-tier §bMeshes§r increase your chances for §drare ores§r and unique drops, giving better yields from each block.
howtoplay.utilitycraft.expanding_resources.p12=Mesh progression goes as follows:\n- §fString Mesh§r\n- §7Flint Mesh§r\n- §6Copper Mesh§r\n- §fIron Mesh§r\n- §eGold Mesh§r\n- §aEmerald Mesh§r\n- §bDiamond Mesh§r\n- §8Netherite Mesh§r
howtoplay.utilitycraft.expanding_resources.p13=Each tier improves what you can get from §fGravel§r, §aDirt§r, and §6Sand§r. Upgrade as your world expands to keep resources flowing.
howtoplay.utilitycraft.expanding_resources.p14=For bulk processing, compress materials like §fCobblestone§r, §fGravel§r, §aDirt§r, and §6Sand§r.
howtoplay.utilitycraft.expanding_resources.p15=§eHammers§r can break compressed blocks down in sequence, turning large batches into the next material much faster.
howtoplay.utilitycraft.expanding_resources.p16=The §eSieve§r also accepts §bcompressed blocks§r. They are faster to process, but yield around §c50%§r of normal blocks, making them quicker but less efficient.
howtoplay.utilitycraft.expanding_resources.p17=With stronger §bMeshes§r, compressed processing, and a steady setup, your early resource loop is ready to scale.
howtoplay.utilitycraft.expanding_resources.p18=For automation, consider §aBountiful Bonsais§r to pair tree farming with your growing production chain.
howtoplay.utilitycraft.expanding_resources.p19=From here, move into §fFirst Steps to Steel§r, where you will unlock §bWater§r, §6Lava§r, §fSteel§r, and your first path into §aautomation§r.
howtoplay.utilitycraft.water_lava_production.h1=Obtaining Water
howtoplay.utilitycraft.water_lava_production.h2=Obtaining Lava
howtoplay.utilitycraft.water_lava_production.h3=Heat Sources
howtoplay.utilitycraft.water_lava_production.h4=Crafting the Crucible
howtoplay.utilitycraft.water_lava_production.p1=In this chapter, you will progress toward §fSteel§r, craft your first §eGenerator§r, power your first §bMachines§r, and begin real §aautomation§r.
howtoplay.utilitycraft.water_lava_production.p2=These materials unlock early automation, farming, and even Nether access.
howtoplay.utilitycraft.water_lava_production.p3=Begin by crafting a §eMortar§r using 3 §fCobblestone§r and 1 §fStone Pebble§r.
howtoplay.utilitycraft.water_lava_production.p4=Use the §eMortar§r with 1 §fGlass Bottle§r and 2 §aSaplings§r to create a §bWater Bottle§r. The Mortar is not consumed.
howtoplay.utilitycraft.water_lava_production.p5=Use §b3 Water Bottles§r on a §eCauldron§r to fill it, then collect your first §bWater Bucket§r with a Bucket.
howtoplay.utilitycraft.water_lava_production.p6=To generate §6Lava§r, use a §eCrucible§r. It converts §fCobblestone§r over time and must be placed above a heat source such as a Torch, Campfire, Fire, or Lava.
howtoplay.utilitycraft.water_lava_production.p7=Stronger heat sources speed up the conversion.
howtoplay.utilitycraft.water_lava_production.p8=Useful heat sources include:\n- Lava or Flowing Lava: 4\n- Soul Fire, Soul Torch, or Soul Campfire: 4\n- Fire: 3\n- Campfire: 3\n- Magma Block: 3\n- Torch: 1
howtoplay.utilitycraft.water_lava_production.p9=Feed §f4 Cobblestone§r into the §eCrucible§r to slowly generate §61 bucket of Lava§r. You can also interact with it using a §bWater Bucket§r to instantly create §5Obsidian§r.
howtoplay.utilitycraft.water_lava_production.p10=To craft a §eCrucible§r, you need §f4 Bricks§r and §64 Mud Bricks§r.
howtoplay.utilitycraft.water_lava_production.p11=§fBricks§r are made by smelting §fClay§r, and Clay can be obtained by sieving §6Sand§r.
howtoplay.utilitycraft.water_lava_production.p12=To make §6Mud Bricks§r, start by creating §6Mud§r: place §aDirt§r and use a §bWater Bottle§r on it to convert it.
howtoplay.utilitycraft.water_lava_production.p13=Combine §6Mud§r with §eWheat§r to make §6Packed Mud§r. Then craft §64 Packed Mud§r into §61 Mud Brick§r. Wheat Seeds are obtained by sieving §aDirt§r.
howtoplay.utilitycraft.water_lava_production.p14=Once you have both §fBricks§r and §6Mud Bricks§r, craft your §eCrucible§r.
howtoplay.utilitycraft.water_lava_production.p15=With stable §bWater§r and §6Lava§r, you have the foundation for §eenergy generation§r and §aautomation§r.
howtoplay.utilitycraft.first_steps_steel.h1=Crafting the SmeltFlare
howtoplay.utilitycraft.first_steps_steel.h2=Creating Brute Steel
howtoplay.utilitycraft.first_steps_steel.h3=Crafting the Workbench
howtoplay.utilitycraft.first_steps_steel.h4=Machinery Era
howtoplay.utilitycraft.first_steps_steel.p1=You've mastered §bresource gathering§r, §bwater§r and §6lava§r production, and §fCobblestone§r generation.
howtoplay.utilitycraft.first_steps_steel.p2=Now it is time to enter metallurgy by creating §fSteel§r, marking the beginning of the §eMachinery Era§r.
howtoplay.utilitycraft.first_steps_steel.p3=To start producing §fSteel§r, you need §fRaw Iron§r, §7Coal§r, and a §eSmeltFlare§r. The SmeltFlare lets you combine raw materials directly in your inventory to craft metal alloys.
howtoplay.utilitycraft.first_steps_steel.p4=To obtain §fPaper§r for this recipe, sieve §aDirt§r to get §aSugar Cane§r, then craft it into Paper.
howtoplay.utilitycraft.first_steps_steel.p5=Once you have a §eSmeltFlare§r, place it in your inventory with §fRaw Iron§r and §7Coal§r. The SmeltFlare merges them into §fBrute Steel§r, a raw alloy that can later be refined.
howtoplay.utilitycraft.first_steps_steel.p6=Smelt §fBrute Steel§r in a §eFurnace§r or use another §eSmeltFlare§r to produce §fSteel Ingots§r. Tip: combine §f9 Brute Steel§r into a §fBrute Block§r to smelt 9 ores at once.
howtoplay.utilitycraft.first_steps_steel.p7=Before building advanced systems, craft a §eWorkbench§r. Every §bMachine§r, §eGenerator§r, and machine §dUpgrade§r is crafted exclusively inside the Workbench.
howtoplay.utilitycraft.first_steps_steel.p8=Here is the §eWorkbench§r recipe.
howtoplay.utilitycraft.first_steps_steel.p9=Congratulations, you have reached the §eMachinery Era§r. From here, your progression shifts from manual crafting into powered production, energy storage, and real §aautomation§r.
howtoplay.utilitycraft.first_steps_steel.p10=Before continuing, keep a supply of §fSteel§r, §fIron§r, §6Copper§r, §cRedstone§r, and §7Coal§r. These materials will carry your first machines, generators, and upgrades.
howtoplay.utilitycraft.first_steps_steel.p11=Your next goal is to craft your first powered §bMachines§r, connect them to §eEnergy§r, and start turning your base into a production system.
howtoplay.utilitycraft.machines.p1=Machines are the core of §aautomation§r in UtilityCraft. Most use §bDorios Energy§r, can auto-output forward, and accept upgrades to improve speed or efficiency.
howtoplay.utilitycraft.machines.h1=Assembler
howtoplay.utilitycraft.machines.p2=The §eAssembler§r crafts items automatically from a §bBlueprint§r made by the Digitizer. Keep the required materials stocked, give it §bEnergy§r, and it will repeat the saved craft. Accepts §aSpeed§r and §bEnergy§r upgrades.
howtoplay.utilitycraft.machines.h2=Autosieve
howtoplay.utilitycraft.machines.p3=The §eAutosieve§r processes gravel, sand, dirt, and other sieveable blocks with a mesh. Better meshes unlock stronger drops and multipliers. Accepts §aSpeed§r and §bEnergy§r upgrades.
howtoplay.utilitycraft.machines.h3=Autofisher
howtoplay.utilitycraft.machines.p4=The §eAutofisher§r generates fishing loot using §eFishing Nets§r. Place it near water or a Sink, insert a net, and power it. Better nets improve rolls, luck, and rare drops. Accepts §aSpeed§r and §bEnergy§r upgrades.
howtoplay.utilitycraft.machines.h4=Block Breaker
howtoplay.utilitycraft.machines.p5=The §eBlock Breaker§r breaks the block directly in front of it. Use it with cobble generators, farms, or block loops where drops need to be collected automatically. Accepts §aSpeed§r and §bEnergy§r upgrades.
howtoplay.utilitycraft.machines.h5=Block Placer
howtoplay.utilitycraft.machines.p6=The §eBlock Placer§r places blocks from its inventory into the space in front of it. Pair it with a Block Breaker for repeatable placement loops. Accepts §aSpeed§r and §bEnergy§r upgrades.
howtoplay.utilitycraft.machines.h6=Crusher
howtoplay.utilitycraft.machines.p7=The §eCrusher§r doubles metal ore processing into dust. This includes Nether Gold Ore giving 2 Gold Dust and Ancient Debris giving 2 Netherite Scrap Dust. Mineral ores use specific yields: Coal gives 4, Quartz gives 6, Lapis or Redstone gives 8, and Diamond or Emerald gives 2 gems. Accepts §aSpeed§r and §bEnergy§r upgrades.
howtoplay.utilitycraft.machines.h7=Digitizer
howtoplay.utilitycraft.machines.p8=The §eDigitizer§r records crafting layouts into reusable §bBlueprints§r. Use Blueprint Paper and the target materials to create patterns for the Assembler. Accepts §aSpeed§r and §bEnergy§r upgrades.
howtoplay.utilitycraft.machines.h8=Electro Press
howtoplay.utilitycraft.machines.p9=The §eElectro Press§r automates plates, compression, and ore reconstruction. It combines §e4 matching Chunks§r into an ore and §e4 Diamond or Emerald Shards§r into a complete gem. Accepts §aSpeed§r and §bEnergy§r upgrades.
howtoplay.utilitycraft.machines.h9=Harvester
howtoplay.utilitycraft.machines.p10=The §eHarvester§r gathers crops and plant blocks in an area. Use §9Range§r upgrades to expand its working area, then power it for automatic farming. Accepts §aSpeed§r, §bEnergy§r, and §9Range§r upgrades.
howtoplay.utilitycraft.machines.h10=Incinerator
howtoplay.utilitycraft.machines.p11=The §eIncinerator§r smelts or burns valid inputs using §bEnergy§r instead of furnace fuel. It fits well into powered processing lines. Accepts §aSpeed§r and §bEnergy§r upgrades.
howtoplay.utilitycraft.machines.h11=Induction Anvil
howtoplay.utilitycraft.machines.p12=The §eInduction Anvil§r repairs durable items with §bEnergy§r. Insert a damaged tool, armor piece, or other durable item and it will repair over time. Accepts §aSpeed§r and §bEnergy§r upgrades.
howtoplay.utilitycraft.machines.h12=Infuser
howtoplay.utilitycraft.machines.p13=The §eInfuser§r combines an input with a catalyst to create infused materials and advanced components. Keep both slots supplied and power the machine. Accepts §aSpeed§r and §bEnergy§r upgrades.
howtoplay.utilitycraft.machines.h13=Magmatic Chamber
howtoplay.utilitycraft.machines.p14=The §eMagmatic Chamber§r handles heat and lava-related processing with item and liquid support. It belongs in more advanced automation lines. Accepts §aSpeed§r and §bEnergy§r upgrades.
howtoplay.utilitycraft.machines.h14=Seed Synthesizer
howtoplay.utilitycraft.machines.p15=The §eSeed Synthesizer§r creates special seeds and plant progression materials through powered synthesis. It has high energy needs, so connect it to stable power. Accepts §aSpeed§r and §bEnergy§r upgrades.
howtoplay.utilitycraft.generators.p1=Generators create §bDorios Energy§r for your machines. Each generator has four tiers, shown from left to right as Tier 1 through Tier 4.
howtoplay.utilitycraft.generators.h1=Furnator
howtoplay.utilitycraft.generators.p2=The §eFurnator§r burns solid fuel into §bEnergy§r. It is the simplest powered generator and works well for early machine setups.
howtoplay.utilitycraft.generators.h2=Magmator
howtoplay.utilitycraft.generators.p3=The §eMagmator§r turns lava into §bEnergy§r. It pairs well with lava production and liquid transport systems.
howtoplay.utilitycraft.generators.h3=Solar Panel
howtoplay.utilitycraft.generators.p4=The §eSolar Panel§r generates §bEnergy§r from sunlight. It is passive and fuel-free, but works best with clear sky access.
howtoplay.utilitycraft.generators.h4=Thermo Generator
howtoplay.utilitycraft.generators.p5=The §eThermo Generator§r produces §bEnergy§r from hot blocks or heat sources. Use it when you want steady power without item fuel.
howtoplay.utilitycraft.generators.h5=Wind Turbine
howtoplay.utilitycraft.generators.p6=The §eWind Turbine§r generates §bEnergy§r from wind. Placement and environment matter, so it works best when set up in open areas.
howtoplay.utilitycraft.generators.h6=Batteries
howtoplay.utilitycraft.generators.p7=§eBatteries§r store §bEnergy§r so your machines can keep working when generation slows down. Higher tiers hold much more power.
howtoplay.utilitycraft.drop_tables.h1=Sieve Mesh Multipliers
howtoplay.utilitycraft.drop_tables.h2=Sieve Block Drops
howtoplay.utilitycraft.drop_tables.h3=Autofisher Fishing Nets
howtoplay.utilitycraft.drop_tables.h4=Autofisher Loot Table
howtoplay.utilitycraft.drop_tables.p1=Use these §eDrop Tables§r to plan your §bSieve§r and §bAutofisher§r setups. Tiers control what can drop, and multipliers increase output when a recipe succeeds.
howtoplay.utilitycraft.drop_tables.p2=The §bSieve§r accepts UtilityCraft meshes and applies each mesh multiplier to its processing results.
howtoplay.utilitycraft.drop_tables.p3=Each Sieve block below has its own table. §eMin Tier§r shows the required mesh tier number and material, and chances are base chances before mesh multipliers.
howtoplay.utilitycraft.drop_tables.p4=§bCompressed blocks§r use the same table as their matching base block, but output §ex9 amounts§r.
howtoplay.utilitycraft.drop_tables.p5=The §bAutofisher§r uses §eFishing Nets§r. Better nets increase drop chance and add more rolls, making rare loot easier to obtain.
howtoplay.utilitycraft.drop_tables.p6=This loot table shows the base chance before the fishing net multiplier. Some equipment drops may also roll durability and enchantments.
howtoplay.utilitycraft.drop_tables.p7=Custom addons may register extra §bSieve§r or §bAutofisher§r drops with script events, so integrated worlds may show more results than these base tables.

